Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Plea/sentencing hearing on February 6, 2023 at 10:00 am.

10:20 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Tyland C Parker appeared by Zoom video, in custody at MHOC.  Attorney Brandon K. Carlson in court for Tyland C Parker.  Prosecuting attorney Shawn N Woller in court for the State of Wisconsin. All parties have agreed that some may have the hearing conducted remotely. This hearing has met the statutory standards for video conferencing. Atty. Carlson provides an update; he has discovery as well as an offer but notes his client has plea and sentencing in his Milwaukee County cases and would like to set this matter for projected plea and sentencing after his Milwaukee County cases.  No objection by the State.  Court will adjourn for projected plea and sentencing into January 2023.  Court will have the defendant appear by video from the facility he is currently in for the next court date unless Atty. Carlson advises the court the defendant would prefer to appear in person by OTP.
Plea/sentencing hearing scheduled for February 6, 2023 at 10:00 am.

10:38 AM; Case called for Hearing. Prosecuting attorney Kristi J Gordon in court for the State of Wisconsin.   Attorney Brandon K. Carlson in court for Tyland C Parker.  Court notes the defendant was supposed to be by Zoom from Milwaukee County Jail but was advised the defendant was moved to MHOC so the clerk's office was not able to set up a new video appearance for today.  The Court will waive the defendant's appearance for today.  Atty. Carlson provides an update, he is still waiting for discovery in both matters.  Atty. Carlson requests a further proceedings date in about 30-45 days.  Court adjourns for further proceedings.  Defendant to appear by video from MHOC for the next court date.
Hearing scheduled for October 24, 2022 at 10:00 am.
